{{no footnotes|date=July 2017}}

'''Okobo people''' are native to the [[Okobo, Nigeria|Okobo]] local government area in Akwa Ibom State of [[Nigeria]]. They are subdivided into two major clans: Odu and Eta.

== References ==

* {{cite book |author=Essesien Ntekim |title=OKOBO: Story of a Nigerian People |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QvD8FdMTDSMC&pg=PP1 |date=21 May 2013 |publisher=Xlibris |isbn=978-1-4797-9114-9 }}

[[Category:Ethnic groups in Nigeria]]

{{refimprove|date=November 2016}}
A '''public switched data network''' ('''PSDN''') is a network for providing data services via a system of multiple [[wide-area network]]s, similar in concept to the [[public switched telephone network]] (PSTN).<ref name=bagad>{{cite book|last1=Bagad|title=Telecommunication Switching Systems and Networks|date=2009|publisher=Technical Publications|isbn=9788184315905|pages=344|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=VfPST6NEggEC&pg=SA6-PA4&dq=psdn&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiLpPSoi8TQAhUaOsAKHdAABVQ4ChDoAQgwMAQ#v=onepage&q=psdn&f=false|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref> A PSDN may use a variety of switching technologies, including [[packet switching]], [[circuit switching]], and [[message switching]].<ref name=bagad /> A packet-switched PSDN may also be called a packet-switched data network.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hura and Singal|title=Data and Computer Communications: Networking and Internetworking|date=2001|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=9780849309281|pages=1168|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=BViV0PoH_voC&pg=PA529&dq=psdn&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi44OGZi8TQAhXqI8AKHd8YBL4Q6AEILTAE#v=onepage&q=psdn&f=false|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Mazda|first1=Fraidoon|title=Focal Illustrated Dictionary of Telecommunications|date=2013|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=9781136121029|pages=704|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=i5ZNAGQOX18C&pg=PA497&dq=%22packet+switched%22+%22public+switched%22+PSDN&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjdrJeDicTQAhXII8AKHXNIBdkQ6AEIGzAA#v=snippet&q=psdn&f=false|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>

Originally the term PSDN referred only to [[Packet Switch Stream]] (PSS), an [[X.25]]-based packet-switched network, mostly used to provide leased-line connections between [[local area network]]s and the Internet using  [[permanent virtual circuit]]s (PVCs).{{cn|date=November 2016}} Today, the term may refer not only to [[Frame Relay]] and [[Asynchronous Transfer Mode]] (ATM), both providing PVCs, but also to [[Internet Protocol]] (IP), [[GPRS]], and other [[packet-switching]] techniques.

Whilst there are several technologies that are superficially similar to the PSDN, such as [[Integrated Services Digital Network]] (ISDN) and the [[Digital Subscriber Line]] (DSL) technologies, they are not examples of it.{{cn|date=November 2016}} ISDN utilizes the PSTN circuit-switched network, and DSL uses point-to-point [[circuit switching]] communications overlaid on the PSTN local loop (copper wires), usually utilized for access to a packet-switched broadband IP network.

