{{Telecomm-stub}}

{{use dmy|date=October 2018}} On 28 June 2017, an arms theft at a military base in [[Tancos]], Portugal was discovered. The stolen weapons reportedly included 1,450 [[9 mm caliber]] [[Cartridge (firearms)|cartridges]], 150 [[hand grenade]]s, 44 [[anti-tank grenade]]s, 18 [[tear gas]] grenades, 264 units of [[plastic explosive]]s, and 102 [[explosive charge]]s.<ref name=bbc2017>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-40479221|title=Portuguese president speaks out over stolen weapons arsenal|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=3 July 2017|accessdate=13 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=guardian2017>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jul/03/grenades-and-plastic-explosives-stolen-from-portuguese-arsenal|title= Grenades and plastic explosives stolen from Portuguese arsenal|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=3 July 2017|first=Sam|last=Jones|accessdate=13 October 2018}}</ref> Following an anonymous tip-off, some of the weapons were found in [[Chamusca]] on 18 October 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theportugalnews.com/news/pj-police-recover-arsenal-of-weapons-stolen-from-army-base/43546|title=PJ police recover arsenal of weapons stolen from army base|work=[[The Portugal News]]|date=19 October 2017|accessdate=13 October 2018}}</ref>
An investigation into the recovery of the weapons led to the September 2018 arrests of six military officials from the [[National Republican Guard (Portugal)|National Republican Guard]] and the [[Polícia Judiciária Militar|Military Judicial Police]] (PJM), including the head of the PJM,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.euronews.com/2018/09/26/head-of-portuguese-military-police-arrested-after-links-with-armaments-theft-discovered|title=Portugal's military police chief accused of cover up over massive arms theft|publisher=[[Euronews]]|date=26 September 2018|first=Cristina Abellan|last=Matamoros|accessdate=13 October 2018}}</ref> [[Coronel Luís Augusto Vieira]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theportugalnews.com/news/head-of-loule-gnr-arrested-by-pj-police/46950|title=Head of Loulé GNR arrested by PJ police|work=[[The Portugal News]]|date=25 September 2018|accessdate=13 October 2018}}</ref> Amid accusations of a military cover-up of the arms theft, [[Ministry of National Defence (Portugal)|Minister of National Defence]] [[José Alberto Azeredo Lopes]] resigned on 12 October 2018. Azeredo Lopes has denied any involvement in the alleged cover-up.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-portugal-defence-resignation/portugal-defense-minister-quits-amid-probe-of-theft-cover-up-idUSKCN1MM2D7|title=Portugal defense minister quits amid probe of theft cover-up|publisher=[[Reuters]]|date=12 October 2018|accessdate=13 October 2018}}</ref>
